[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Rugby Football Union [WAS0029][bold]&#xa0;
[normal]About the RFU[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]Women’s rugby in England
[normal] has seen a steady increase in parti
[normal]cipation and interest in 
[normal]recent years from a very low base a decade ago
[normal].  
[normal]Prior to 2011 the 
[normal]Rugby Football Union 
[normal]for Women 
[normal]was a separate entity to the RFU.  Following 
[normal]integration
[normal] the RFU’s full resources have been put behind developing women’s rugby at all levels of the Game.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]With the platform of the Women’s 
[normal]Rugby World Cup 
[normal]in 201
[normal]4
[normal], a home
[normal] Rugby World Cup in 2015 and rugby sevens entering the Olympics in 2016
[normal] for both men and women
[normal], there is a huge opportunity for 
[normal]the RFU 
[normal]to broaden the appeal of the Game amongst women.  The RFU is also working to widen 
[normal]access
[normal] to women workin
[normal]g and volunteering in rugby at all the levels of the Game, as we recognise that a balanced workforce will strengthen 
[normal]the Game
[normal].
[normal]  As this submission will show, English rugby has developed from a heavily male dominated sport 
[normal]to a more balanced one 
[normal]in just a f
[normal]ew years, and this progress will continue.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Female engagement in rugby union in England is far higher than participation, suggesting that there 
[normal]are significant perception
[normal] or practical barriers to women playing rugby.  This submission 
[normal]considers these barr
[normal]iers and makes some recommendations to the Committee on how public policy might help women and girl’s rugby to flourish further.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The RFU’s submission is divided into core areas of activity 
[normal]–
[normal] 
[normal]performance, media, commercial, fan engagement, leadership, 
[normal]facilities and rugby in schools.  The RFU has also made some recommendations to the Committee.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Performance rugby[bold]1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]England women’s teams are world beaters.  The 
[normal]Senior
[normal] 1
[normal]5-a-side team has
[normal] enjoyed a sustained period of success coming 2
[normal]nd
[normal] place in the last thr
[normal]ee successive World Cups 2002, 2006 and 2010 in England.  They have won seven RBS 6 Nations titles since 
[normal]2003,
[normal] and six Grand Slams in the last decade.  The Senior 7 a-side team are also very successful, and came runners up in the 2013 7s World Series.
[normal]1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]RFU supports three women’s elite teams – 
[normal]Senior
[normal] 15–a-side, Senior 7-a-side, and Under 20s 15-a-side.  Previously more teams have been supported but a decision was made to consolidate the offering to ensure quality was higher and support better for those to
[normal]p teams.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There are approximately 1,000 women playing rugby to a very high level within the talent pathway. The talent pathway focuses on talented players from U15 to senior level.  The markers used to assess the health of the game have been agreed with S
[normal]port England. 
[normal]Case Study 1: [bold]Player, [bold]Sarah Hunter[bold] 
[normal]England XIs Captain
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sarah began playing rugby league aged nine at primary school and started in union five years later. Born in Newcastle-upon-Tyne, Sarah attended Goathland Primary and Longbenton
[normal] Community College in North Tyneside before gaining a BSc in Sport Science and Mathematics at Loughborough University. She is now a RFU University Rugby Development Officer for the South West.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Her achievements feature winning the British Universities Cham
[normal]pionship with Loughborough, captaining Lichfield from 2005-09, the North East U18 and Northumberland U16 sides. Her international triumphs span the Six Nations five times, together with the European Championship, Nations Cup and European Trophy twice each.
[normal] Personal accolades are players’ player awards at Novocastrians, Lichfield, Loughborough University and the England Academy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU invested approximately
[normal] £2.5m on women
[normal]’s 
[normal]elite rugby
[normal] last year, which 
[normal]includes talent
[normal] identification and development
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] This
[normal] is lower than the investment in the men’s elite programme, due to a number of factors including that the RFU has to pay release fees from Premiership clubs
[normal] 
[normal]for the men.  
[normal]The RFU has been relatively well placed internationally in investment in the women’s 
[normal]7s programme
[normal].  
[normal]The England 15s programme is one of the best resour
[normal]ced in the world which allows England
[normal] to compete at the top level.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]1.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Though the sponsorship value of the women’s Game is significantly lower than the men’s at present
[normal],
[normal] which is why we offer 
[normal]sponsors rights to both (see 3.1)
[normal], the RFU is committed to investing in women’s rugby over and above the income it 
[normal]currently 
[normal]generates
[normal].  
[normal]The RFU does not receive any public funding from UK Sport to support the elite women’s programme but does from
[normal] Sport En
[normal]gland through to 2014.  Public investment in women’s rugby is vital, and we urge the Government to continue to invest in women
[normal]’s rugby
[normal].
