[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6[bold]. [bold]Grassroots rugby[bold]6.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU sees f
[normal]emale participation in rugby as a significant growth are
[normal]a.  The full integration of the RFUW into the RFU means that the RFU’s full resources, including 
[normal]585
[normal] support staff based at Twickenham
[normal] and around the country
[normal], are 
[normal]behind growing the women’s Game at grassroots. 
[normal]  As mentioned previously
[normal],
[normal] Rugby Union will 
[normal]also 
[normal]see a huge spike of interest due to 
[normal]a home men’s
[normal] Rugby World Cup and 
[normal]rugby 7s entering the Olympic Games in Rio, and 
[normal]the RFU is
[normal] keen to capitalise 
[normal]on 
[normal]this to increase participation amongst 
[normal]both 
[normal]men and women.
[normal]6.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Female participation is currently low comp
[normal]ared to other sports
[normal],
[normal] but growing rapidly with 
[normal]15,000 women and girls playing contact rugby each week, an increase of 90% since 2004[bold].  We plan to increase this by a further 10,000 by 2017 through targeted work with 
[normal]2
[normal]00 
[normal]of our member 
[normal]clubs across England.
[normal]6.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]3
[normal]00 
[normal]rugby 
[normal]clubs in England have a women and girls offering with 60% of clubs offer girls rugby at U13 level, 40% at U15, 30% at U18, 25% 
[normal]at 
[normal]Senior
[normal] level
[normal].
[normal]  The RFU is working with clubs to review 
[normal]this as the offer in clubs 
[normal]appears to be
[normal] narrowing at the age spectrum where we want to see higher participation.  These figure
[normal]s suggest significant drop off
[normal] in their teenage years, and we hope our work with clubs will help us understand why this is happening and what we can do to keep more youn
[normal]g women in the Game.
[normal]6.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU has developed a Women and Girls
[normal]’
[normal] strategy based on extensive research with existing female rugby players, females participating in other sports, and less active females.  The key strands of the strategy are:
[normal]6.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]For #i &amp; #ii the
[normal] RFU 
[normal]is 
[normal]focusing on engag
[normal]ement with 
[normal]200 rugby
[normal] clubs to identify the challenges clubs face in attracting women and girls, and how these can most effectively be overcome.
[normal]  More than 50 clubs are part of the Year 1 
[normal]regional 
[normal]Cluster
[normal]s
[normal] and 
[normal]are working with the RFU’s field team to increa
[normal]se female parti
[normal]cipation at their
[normal] clubs.
[normal]6.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU also expect
[normal]s
[normal] to see increases in female participation from the resource we are putting into modified forms of the Game, such as O2 Touch rugby, as our research shows 
[normal]these appeal more to women and girls
[normal].  O2 Touch is a join initiative from the RFU and long-standing partner O2, and is part of the RFU’s plans to increase participation in rugby as part of the 2015 Rugby World Cup Legacy.  There are currently more than 50 O2 Touch Centres in rugby clubs and 
[normal]Universities across the 
[normal]country,
[normal] and by 2014 there will be a further 100. The advantages of Touch is that it is great for fitness, men and women can play together, and the rules are very simple so it is an easy way to start playing rugby
[normal] – all of these poi
[normal]nts address barriers to women and girls starting to play rugby
[normal].  Of those signed up to the O2 Touch rugby programme, 18% are female.  This is a good start but we aim to increase the proportion of female participants further
[normal] as overall participation with To
[normal]uch rugby increases
[normal].
[normal]6.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Grassroots rugby relies on the support of England rugby’s 60,000 volunteers.  The RFU aims to increase volunteering in rugby by both men and women.  The RFU’s development team is working with potential volunteers to identify how the RF
[normal]U could attract more female volunteers to support their local rugby clubs.  
[normal]Case Study 
[normal]9
[normal] is on Sophie Morris, a volunteer at Millwall 
[normal]R
[normal]ugby 
[normal]C
[normal]lub and a great example of
[normal] how volunteers support our
[normal] member clubs. 
[normal]Case Study 8: Club volunteer, Sophie Morris [bold]Sophie is a Sponsorship and Marketing Consultant and volunteer.  Her involvement in rugby began when she was a Director of Marketing for a Financial Services firm which sponsored the Barbarians games at Twickenham.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In 2012 she wanted to do some volunte
[normal]er work and searched on a Government website for opportunities and found Millwall Rugby Club.  
[normal]The Club welcomed her expertise and she was appointed the
[normal] Development Officer, looking after sponsorship, marketing and press.  Having not played team sport sinc
[normal]e school, she took up Touch and then 
[normal]moved on to contact rugby, playing for Millwall’s ladies team.  Sophie now sits on the Essex County RFU Development Committee.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Among Sophie’s many achievements are increasing sponsorship income to Millwall Rugby Club b
[normal]y more than 500%, and the recruitment of the club’s first ever sponsor of the Ladies team.  Sophie sits on one of the RFU’s six regional Rugby World Cup Activation and Legacy Groups which were set up to capitalise on the opportunity of 2015 to increase par
[normal]ticipation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]All the above roles are voluntary, and Sophie has recently set up her own Marketing consultancy, specialising in rugby sponsorship.  She is keen to promote sponsorship in the women’s side of the Game.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There are 
[normal]approximately 2000
[normal] community rugby clubs in England and 
[normal]of these
[normal] 77% have security of tenure over their ground
[normal].  The RFU supports clubs through loans, grants and advic
[normal]e to ensure that these
[normal] facilities are 
[normal]high-quality and well managed.
[normal]  Clubs will drive increases in female 
[normal]participation and so it is vital that improvements are made to facilities to make them more attractive to women, although facility improvements will of course benefit all participants.
[normal]7.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Constituent Bodies (governance structure which broadly mirrors county b
[normal]orders) work with local Rugby Development Officers (50 full time RFU employees) to identify the needs of rugby clubs within the context of national priorities.
[normal]  
[normal]One of the factors the RFU asks clubs and CBs to consider when seeking investment is the club’s
[normal] plans for women and girls activity.
[normal]7.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Research by the RFU and the Women’s Sport and Fitness Foundation found that the main barriers to women and girls playing rugby are the changing and clubhouse facilities.  
[normal]Between 2003 and 2012 the RFU and Rugby Football
[normal] Foundation has invested £23.4m of grants and loans in 763 clubhouse projects with a total project cost of £72m, focusing on improved changing facilities and clubhouses. The improvements to clubhouses are designed to meet “RFU Guidance Note 5: Clubhouses a
[normal]nd Changing Rooms” which has been developed to produce facilities that meet the needs of all users of rugby clubs (adult, youth and child, male and female). A large number of these projects are focused on supporting clubs to grow the number of women and gi
[normal]rls teams as well as male provision, but we do not count them separately.
[normal] 
[normal]7.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU plans to 
[normal]invest £10m into 500 rugby clubs as part of its Lead Up and Legacy Programme [bold](
[normal]the
[normal] RFU’s legacy plan to use the 2015 RWC to grow participation). Changing room improv
[normal]ements remain a key part of this programm
[normal]e and in the first round £600,000 went to eight projects. Round Three
[normal] of the programme is particularly focused at transforming social spaces in clubhouses with £2.5m investment. The RFU is developing support and gui
[normal]dance for clubs participating in this round to design and furnish these spaces in line with the findings of the RFU’s work with the Women’s Sport and Fitness Foundation.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8. Rugby in schools[bold]8.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU works in schools, colleges and universities to provide 
[normal]opportu
[normal]nities for girls to play rugby.  Encouraging school age girls to play rugby is vital to the future health of the Game in general participation and elite success.  
[normal]8.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]At primary 
[normal]school 
[normal]age the RFU want to see 
[normal]students
[normal] receive a broad and balanced PE ex
[normal]perience, and then get more opportunities to be involved in sport specific activities and pla
[normal]y rugby in Key Stages 3 and 4.  
[normal]The RFU’s primary focus for delivering schools-based rugby is at secondary level as this is where we can have the bigger impact on 
[normal]participation in encouraging young people to tak
[normal]e up and continue playing rugby beyond school age.
[normal]  
[normal]8.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There are 3126 schools affiliated to the England Rugby Football Schools Union, many of which have good quality sporting facilities.
[normal] As part of the Rugby Wo
[normal]rld Cup legacy work, last year the RFU launched 
[normal]the 
[normal]All Schools 
[normal]Programme 
[normal]to 
[normal]help
[normal] more state secondary schools to offer rugby[bold] to their students (Case Study 
[normal]10
[normal]).
[normal]8.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU provides coaching, kit, equipment and teacher training, and in a typical year our natio
[normal]nwide community rugby coaches would impact on an estimated 750 secondary schools.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case Study [bold]10[bold]: All Schools Programme [bold]In 2012 
[normal]The RFU launched All Schools.  
[normal]All Schools was founded on the principles that ALL schools can play rugby, ALL of t
[normal]he 
[normal]children in the school can
[normal] play, and rugby has a positive impact on ALL of the school. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The RFU provides tailored support to each school, depending on their needs, challenges and opportunities
[normal] over a three year period
[normal].  The RFU are therefore pleased that 
[normal]more than half of the schools in Phase 1 opted to have girls-only or mixed sessions in their schools[bold].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]All Schools is one of seven area areas identified by the RFU to deliver the greatest participation legacy for the game in the lead up to the Rugby World 
[normal]Cup 2015 and beyond.  The RFU has set up All Schools to 
[normal]help more state schools that haven’t traditionally played rugby[bold] to offer the Game to their students.  We aim to help 400 state secondary schools new to rugby to become self-sufficient rugby playing sc
[normal]hools and linked into their local rugby clubs by the 2015 Rugby World Cup.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Schools have been identified in small clusters, allowing them to play rugby against each other locally.  The schools in Phase 1 2012-13 (100) and Phase 2 2013-14 (an additional 100
[normal]) have been selected on a number of factors including: local rugby club need for young players, proximity to potential RWC2015 venues, and areas of the country that to date haven’t had a large rugby union following.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Rugby generates whole school improvemen
[normal]t and the RFU encourages coaches and teachers to help youngsters understand and practice rugby’s core values – 
[normal]Teamwork, Respect, Enjoyment, Discipline, [bold]Sportsmanship[bold].  Teachers from schools which have participated in Year 1 have reported improving behavio
[normal]ur, enhanced learning and increasing self-esteem amongst students.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Canterbury, the kit partner of England Rugby, is the Official Partner of All Schools.  Each school taking part in the programme is given the opportunity to attend a Canterbury kit design
[normal] workshop.  The students design their own team rugby shirt, whilst learning about the core values of rugby, the pride associated with the shirt and the importance of colours, logos and emblems, which is made up and presented to the schools at Twickenham.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]9. [bold]Conclusions and recommendations[bold] 
[normal]9.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU warmly welcomes the Committee’s focus on women and girls
[normal]’
[normal] sport.  Much progress has been made in recent years in developing women’s rugby from grassroots to high performance, and the RFU is keen to work with our partners and stakeholders to 
[normal]enco
[normal]urage more females to play
[normal]. 
[normal]9.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The RFU makes the following policy sugg
[normal]estions to the Committee for Members’ consideration:
[normal]9.2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Stability for [bold]Government[bold]’s sport[bold] policy and public investment[bold] in grassroots sport[bold]-
[normal] 
[normal]National Governing Bodies are a key delivery partner for increasing participation amongst women and girls
[normal]. Stability in 
[normal]Government 
[normal]policy
[normal] and investment
[normal] will
[normal] allow 
[normal]us and other 
[normal]NGBs
[normal] to concentrate on delivering the agreed participation outcomes.
[normal]9.2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Public investment in elite sport[bold] – 
[normal]The RFU urges continued public investment in elite women’s sport, and would welcome 
[normal]consideration of whether sports not currently supported may be eligible in the future
[normal].
[normal]9.2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Incentivise girls[bold]’[bold] and women’s opportunities for grassroots clubs[bold]- 
[normal]The 
[normal]Government could consider additional rate relief for comm
[normal]unity clubs which offered opportunities f
[normal]or girls and women.
[normal] 
[normal]9.2.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Promoting media coverage[bold]- 
[normal]the Government should continue to encourage 
[normal]the 
[normal]media 
[normal]to provide more coverage of
[normal] women’s sport
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]use its 
[normal]own 
[normal]media platforms
[normal] and assets
[normal] to promote women’s successes
[normal].
